WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:12.384
Two setups can both look like winners and still quietly
destroy you together, if they lose on the same days. This
lab is how you catch that before it ever happens.

2
00:00:12.984 --> 00:00:28.104
It's the Correlation lab, in Step four. It takes every
move you've loaded, turns each one into a daily win-loss
series, and compares every single pair. The question it's
answering is simple. Do these two setups zig and zag
together, or independently?

3
00:00:28.704 --> 00:00:41.784
Green means independent. They smooth each other out. Red
means they win and lose on the same days, which stacks
your risk instead of spreading it. A whole portfolio of
red is really just one big bet wearing a bunch of
different hats.

4
00:00:42.384 --> 00:00:58.224
But correlated isn't just one thing. There are six lenses
here, each asking a sharper question. Pearson is the
everyday one. Do their daily results rise and fall
together. Spearman ranks the days instead, so one monster
outlier day can't fake a relationship.

5
00:00:58.824 --> 00:01:14.040
Now the ones that actually save accounts. Downside looks
only at the losing days, because who cares if they rise
together, you care if they fall together. Drawdown asks
whether their slumps line up. And Co-drawdown is the plain
percentage of days both were underwater at the same time.

6
00:01:14.640 --> 00:01:28.728
And the most important one of all. Tail Risk. It looks
only at each move's very worst days and asks if they land
on the same dates. Because average correlation hides the
one thing that truly blows up accounts. Your nightmare
days all arriving together.

7
00:01:29.328 --> 00:01:41.112
And it reads the whole grid for you. Your most redundant
pair, basically the same bet. Your best diversifier to add
to smooth the curve. And the tail-risk pair most likely to
crash together. Do not stack those two.

8
00:01:41.712 --> 00:01:47.616
Diversification isn't owning more setups. It's owning
setups that don't fall apart on the very same day.
